": [{"role": "user", "content": "should we not include all milestone columns?", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.412962+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "No\\u2014don\\u2019t include *all* milestone columns in the **Milestone node\\u2019s default mapping/query**.\\n\\n### Why\\n- This node is defined as a **milestone taxonomy/definition framework**, not \\u201call milestone values per project.\\u201d Pulling 700\\u2013800 columns makes the node behave like a *Project wide table extract*, not a reusable milestone concept.\\n- It\\u2019s also expensive/unwieldy (wide payloads, hard to filter, hard to use downstream).\\n\\n### What we should do instead\\n**Keep Milestone mapped to the same master table** (since there is no normalized milestone-definition table), but change the access pattern to:\\n1) Return a *thin* set of identifying columns (project id/site/market/etc.) **plus**\\n2) A *parameterized* way to fetch **only the milestone(s) requested** (e.g., `ms_1970_integration_complete_actual`, `pj_a_4225_construction_start_finish`), not everything.\\n\\nIn practice, we usually support two use cases:\\n- **List available milestone columns** (metadata discovery: \\u201cwhat milestones exist?\\u201d)\\n- **Fetch milestone values for one/few milestone columns** for a project cohort\\n\\n### Next question (so I implement correctly)\\nDo you want the Milestone node API to work like:\\nA) `get_milestone(project_id=..., milestone_cols=[...])` \\u2192 returns those columns only (wide-but-small)  \\nor  \\nB) `get_milestone_long(project_id=...)` \\u2192 returns rows like `(project_id, milestone_code, milestone_value)` (normalized \\u201clong\\u201d shape, created via SQL/Python unpivot)\\n\\nIf you pick **A**, we can do it purely in SQL templating. If you pick **B**, we\\u2019ll likely need Python to unpivot (or dynamic SQL), but it becomes much more \\u201cMilestone-like\\u201d analytically.", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413006+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "user", "content": "let\'s go with B", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413019+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "Got it \\u2014 we should switch the **Milestone** node to a *long/normalized view* (B): one row per `(project, milestone_code, milestone_value)` generated from the wide project table.\\n\\nBefore I implement the mapping + Python unpivot, I need to confirm **which milestone columns are in-scope** (otherwise we\\u2019ll accidentally unpivot non-milestone attributes and explode row counts).\\n\\nFrom the sample, milestone-like columns appear to fall into these families:\\n- `ms_####_*` (e.g., `ms_1970_integration_complete_actual`, `ms_1559_*_so_number`, etc.)\\n- `pj_a_####_*_finish` / `pj_p_####_*_finish` (actual/plan finishes for project activities)\\n- Possibly `magenta_ms_####_actual` / `magenta_####_plan`\\n\\nI\\u2019m going to quickly profile the table to count columns by prefix so we can choose the right families.\\n\\n\\n\\nOnce I see counts, I\\u2019ll implement **Milestone (long)** as:\\n- **Key**: keep table PK as `id` for base rows, but the *logical* key becomes composite `(pj_project_id, milestone_code)` in the returned dataset\\n- **Label**: `milestone_code`\\n- **Python function**: query thin project identifiers + all milestone columns in-scope, then unpivot to long records\\n- **Caveat**: unpivot is computed (not stored), and row volume = `projects \\u00d7 milestone_columns_in_scope`\\n\\nOne more decision for you (fast):\\n- Should we include **only `ms_%`** columns, or include **both `ms_%` + `pj_a_%` + `pj_p_%`**?  \\nMy recommendation: start with **`ms_%` only** (cleanest \\u201cmilestone\\u201d namespace), then optionally expand.\\n\\n**Query Results (SELECT \\n  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE column_name LIKE \'ms\\\\_%\' ES...):**\\n```\\n[\\n  {\\n    \\"ms_cols\\": 153,\\n    \\"pj_a_cols\\": 143,\\n    \\"pj_p_cols\\": 142,\\n    \\"magenta_cols\\": 8,\\n    \\"total_cols\\": 776\\n  }\\n]\\n```", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413026+00:00", "updates_applied": ["python_function", "reasoning_summary", "caveats", "sql_template", "sample_data"]}, {"role": "user", "content": "let\'s go ahead with ms_cols", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413066+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413072+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "user", "content": "let\'s go ahead with ms_cols", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413079+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "Agreed \\u2014 we\\u2019ll scope the **Milestone (long)** output to **only the `ms_%` columns** in `stg_ndpd_mbt_tmobile_macro_combined`. That gives us ~153 milestone fields, which is a manageable long-form expansion.\\n\\n### What will change (Milestone node behavior)\\n- Returns **one row per project per milestone column**:\\n  - `pj_project_id`\\n  - `s_site_id`, `m_market`, `m_area` (helpful context; we can trim later)\\n  - `milestone_code` (e.g., `ms_1970_integration_complete_actual`)\\n  - `milestone_value` (raw value as text; we\\u2019ll preserve nulls)\\n- This is a **computed/unpivoted view** (not a physical table).\\n\\n### Implementation approach\\nBecause SQL unpivot across 153 columns is awkward without dynamic SQL, we\\u2019ll do:\\n1) SQL: pull the small set of identifiers + all `ms_%` columns for the filtered project set\\n2) Python: unpivot into long records\\n\\nI\\u2019ll update the mapping to:\\n- set `label_column` to `milestone_code`\\n- set a new SQL template (thin identifiers + all `ms_%` columns)\\n- regenerate Python to perform the unpivot", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413085+00:00", "updates_applied": ["table_name", "key_column", "label_column", "sql_template", "python_function", "reasoning_summary", "caveats", "sample_data"]}, {"role": "user", "content": "correct", "timestamp": "2026-03-02T14:02:55.413093+00:00", "updates_applied": []}, {"role": "assistant